const faqSchema={"@context": "https://schema.org", "@type": "FAQPage", "mainEntity": [{"@type": "Question", "name": "What is the biggest disadvantage of a reverse mortgage?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The single biggest disadvantage of reverse mortgage products involves the compound interest accumulation that exponentially depletes your home equity over time. Unlike traditional loans where you make payments to reduce principal, reverse mortgage balances grow every month as interest compounds on itself continuously."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Can you lose your house with a reverse mortgage?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "You cannot lose your house through foreclosure as long as you meet three basic ongoing obligations. You must live in the home as your primary residence, maintain property insurance coverage, and pay property taxes on time. Fail any of these requirements and foreclosure becomes possible."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What Suze Orman says about reverse mortgages?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Financial expert Suze Orman has historically advised extreme caution with reverse mortgages, calling them \"last resort\" options only after exhausting all alternatives. She emphasizes the high costs and compound interest make them expensive solutions requiring careful consideration."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Who benefits most from reverse mortgages?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Seniors aged 75-80 with substantial home equity, limited retirement savings, and strong desire to age in place benefit most from reverse mortgage products. This demographic maximizes benefits while minimizing long-term compound interest impacts compared to younger borrowers."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What happens if you live longer than your reverse mortgage?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "You cannot outlive your reverse mortgage or be forced from your home when the loan balance grows to exceed the property value. The non-recourse protection guarantees you can live in the home as long as you maintain property obligations regardless of growing debt."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How does a reverse mortgage affect Social Security and Medicare?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Reverse mortgage proceeds don't affect Social Security benefits whatsoever because they represent loan advances rather than earned income. Your Social Security check continues at exactly the same amount regardless of reverse mortgage distributions received."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What disqualifies you from getting a reverse mortgage?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Age represents the primary reverse mortgage disqualification\u2014all borrowers on the title must be at least 62 years old. If your spouse is under 62, special provisions apply but substantially reduce available proceeds compared to both spouses qualifying."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Can family members take over a reverse mortgage?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Family members cannot assume or take over reverse mortgages in their original form. The loan becomes due when the last surviving borrower permanently leaves the home, requiring full repayment through sale, refinancing, or cash payment."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How much money do you actually get from a reverse mortgage?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The amount you receive from a reverse mortgage depends on your age, home value, and current interest rates. Generally, borrowers age 62 can access approximately 40-50% of home value, while those age 80+ can access 60-75% of value."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Is it better to get a HELOC or a reverse mortgage?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "HELOCs serve financially stable seniors better when they have sufficient income to afford monthly payments comfortably. Lower interest rates and flexible repayment make HELOCs more cost-effective for those who can qualify and make payments."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What are the alternatives to reverse mortgages for seniors?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Downsizing represents the most common reverse mortgage alternative, allowing seniors to sell expensive homes and purchase smaller properties for cash. The equity difference provides years or decades of supplemental income without any loan costs."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Can you sell your home if you have a reverse mortgage?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "You can sell your home with a reverse mortgage at any time without penalty or prepayment fees. The reverse mortgage balance gets paid off at closing like any other mortgage lien, with remaining proceeds distributed to you."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What happens to a reverse mortgage when both spouses die?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "When both spouses with a reverse mortgage die, the loan becomes immediately due and payable. The lender sends notification to the estate executor or heirs explaining repayment options and timelines available for resolution."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Do you pay property taxes with a reverse mortgage?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "You remain responsible for paying property taxes throughout your reverse mortgage term. These taxes don't get rolled into the loan balance automatically\u2014you must pay them annually or through monthly installments like homeowners with traditional mortgages."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How does the interest rate on a reverse mortgage work?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Reverse mortgage interest rates come in two structures: fixed rates or adjustable rates. Fixed rates remain constant throughout the loan term but require taking proceeds as a lump sum at closing, eliminating flexibility."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Can reverse mortgage be refinanced?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Reverse mortgages can be refinanced into new reverse mortgages when circumstances change. Common refinancing reasons include accessing additional equity as home values increase, adding a spouse who previously didn't qualify, or reducing interest rates when markets improve."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What is the average reverse mortgage debt at death?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Average reverse mortgage debt at death varies widely based on initial loan amount, interest rates, time elapsed, and distribution method chosen. Industry data suggests typical balances range from $150,000-250,000 when loans become due."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Are reverse mortgages a good idea in 2024?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Reverse mortgages in 2024 serve appropriate purposes for specific seniors but remain poor choices for many others. Rising interest rates have increased costs substantially compared to 2020-2021 when rates were historically low."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What is the maximum amount you can borrow with a reverse mortgage?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The maximum reverse mortgage amount depends on FHA lending limits that adjust annually. For 2024, the maximum claim amount is $1,149,825 nationally, though higher limits apply in designated high-cost areas where property values exceed national averages."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How do closing costs for reverse mortgages compare to regular mortgages?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Reverse mortgage closing costs substantially exceed traditional mortgage costs, typically ranging from $8,000-15,000 depending on home value and location. These high costs represent a significant disadvantage requiring careful consideration."}}]};
